After the liberal international order
Cambridge — Many analysts believe that the liberal international order ended with China's rise and the election of Donald Trump as U.S. president.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he make an effort to revive the economy?
Perhaps the outcome won't be like that, but he must find some alternative.
Critics are correct in pointing out that the American order since 1945 has not been globally inclusive and has not always been very free.
It excluded more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and included many authoritarian states.
American hegemony is always exaggerated.
Nevertheless, the most powerful countries must take the lead in creating global public goods; otherwise, they will not be provided, and Americans will therefore suffer.
The current pandemic is a good example of this.
A realistic goal of the Biden administration should be to establish an international system based on rules, with different member states participating in handling different matters.
Would China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and the 21st century, both countries were unable to balance American power, while the United States, above the sovereignty, was committed to pursuing the values of freedom.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without obtaining approval from the UN Security Council.
It also supports the United Nations General Assembly's 2005 resolution on "Responsibility to Protect," which aims to provide protection for citizens subjected to cruel treatment by their own governments — a principle the United States later invoked in 2011 to justify bombing Libya in order to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as American arrogance in the post-Cold War era—such as when NATO's intervention in Libya ultimately led to a regime change, leaving Russia and China feeling deceived—while defenders of the action characterize it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
In any case, the growth of China's and Russia's power more strictly limits the scope for liberal interventionist actions.
Then, what remains?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty as stipulated in the UN Charter, which states that a country may only engage in war for self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the situation of occupying neighboring countries by force has been extremely rare, and when it does occur, it incurs a high cost through sanctions (just like Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
In addition, the Security Council often authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled states, while political cooperation has also successfully curbed the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of order based on rules remains crucial.
Specifically in terms of economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Long before the pandemic, China's hybrid national capitalism had already sustained an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will lead to the decoupling of global supply chains, especially when national security is threatened.
Although China has complained that the United States is blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the U.S. stance is consistent with its claims of sovereignty.
After all, China has prevented Google, Facebook, and Twitter from operating within the country for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
At the same time, despite the outbreak of this current crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
In contrast, interdependence in the ecological field creates insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereignty, because threats transcend national borders.
No matter how the process of economic globalization is hindered, environmental globalization will continue, because it is subject to biological and physical laws, which are unaffected by the logic of contemporary geopolitics.
The above issue threatens everyone, but no country is capable of solving it independently.
On issues such as the 2019 coronavirus pandemic and climate change, power also possesses what is called a positive-sum dimension.
Under such premises, merely thinking about exercising power over others is insufficient.
We must also consider this from the perspective of exercising power in conjunction with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization are beneficial to us and others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite differences in ideology, this has not affected cooperation between China and the United States.
The challenge Biden faces is whether the United States and China can cooperate to produce global public goods while competing against each other in traditional great power rivalry areas.
The cyberspace is a new and important issue — because it is partly transnational in nature, but at the same time controlled by sovereign governments.
The Internet has been partially fragmented.
Internet freedom of speech and privacy rules can be established within democratic countries, but these rules would not be recognized by authoritarian states.
As suggested by the Global Commission on Internet Stability, if authoritarians also wish to achieve connectivity, then certain rules prohibiting the tampering with the fundamental structure of the internet would also be in their interest.
But when they use proxies to conduct information warfare or interfere in elections (practices that infringe on sovereignty), it is necessary to reinforce norms through rules such as those negotiated during the Cold War to limit escalation in maritime incidents (although ideological hostility still persists).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly declare the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrence.
Upholding the values of freedom in cyberspace does not mean the United States unilaterally disarms.
In contrast, the United States should distinguish between acceptable public persuasion soft power and hard power such as secret information warfare. When the other side launches a secret information warfare, the United States must certainly respond.
It is permissible for Russia and China to openly broadcast programs and radio, but secret coordinated actions such as manipulating social media are not allowed.
Moreover, the U.S. Congress will continue to criticize these countries' human rights records.
Public opinion polls show that the American public wants to avoid military intervention, but does not want to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
Moreover, the public still values these values.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the liberal international order.
The issue lies in whether the United States can work with its core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while also collaborating with a broader range of countries to manage internationally-based threats such as climate change, pandemic outbreaks, cyberattacks, terrorism, and economic instability through rule-based international institutions.
